George Washington was born on February 22, 1732, in Westmoreland County, Virginia. He grew up on a tobacco plantation and was educated at home by private tutors. At age 20, he inherited Mount Vernon, a large estate in Virginia, and became a successful planter and businessman.

Washington played a key role in the American Revolution, serving as the commander-in-chief of the Continental Army. He led the army to victory over the British and helped to secure American independence. He then served as the first President of the United States from 1789 to 1797, overseeing the establishment of the federal government and the drafting of the U.S. Constitution.

Washington was known for his leadership, courage, and integrity, and is widely regarded as one of America's greatest leaders. He was instrumental in shaping the new nation and setting it on a path to success. Washington died on December 14, 1799, at his home in Mount Vernon, Virginia. He is remembered as a hero and a visionary, and his legacy continues to inspire generations of Americans.